Whether it's ma=
terial things or spiritual, the key to success is to follow portions of one=
's agenda that cause the least inconvenience to others. When one lives with=
 others, some compromises are needed.
=C2=A0
The ability to put oneself in =
the other's shoes, understand how the other person is thinking and be compa=
ssionate to the other's point of view, is a great blessing. Through spiritu=
al sadhana, that ability should eventually be perfected. If one tries consc=
iously, it can come faster.
=C2=A0
Don't confuse compassion for appeasement=
. If I determine that something is too important for me to compromise, I ma=
y not listen to my wife anyway. Yet, if I at least try to understand where =
she is coming from, how she is thinking, what her views and agendas are, I =
can disagree with her without any anger or hatred in my heart. Instead, if =
I keep thinking of my own view and not even try to understand the picture f=
rom her side, my heart may be seething with anger and dissatisfaction.
=C2=
=A0
Compassion allows us to do the right thing without negative vibrations =
weakening the heart.
=C2=A0
Please note that these vibrations in one's hear=
t do resonate in the other person. Even if I am very dexterous with words a=
nd say something sweet and diplomatic, any frustration or dissatisfaction o=
r anger in my heart will express itself as the sub-text behind the words an=
d the other heart does sense it. And, remember - anger feeds anger; dissati=
sfaction feeds dissatisfaction; and, sadness feeds sadness. The gap between=
 2 people widens by sending these negative vibrations to the other.
=C2=A0
=
Instead, if you first try to genuinely feel positive vibrations in your hea=
rt and send them out, even as you disagree and do as you want, it will even=
tually start to balance the other person too.
=C2=A0
