egarding your personal questions:

=C2=A0
Thereare many people who spend ma=
ny more hours in sadhana than I do..
=C2=A0
Yes, I wake up at 4 am and do m=
y homam and japam early on. On weekdays, we are all on our own anyway. On w=
eekends, I am done with everything long before others brush and come downst=
airs.
=C2=A0
There are several temples and satsangs nearby, but I hardly go=
 to them. My homam room is my temple and my satsang.

=C2=A0

As for saattw=
ik diet, I cook kichidi for myself and don't require anybody to cook for me=
. Also, I do not force anybody else to eat it, though they may eat it rarel=
y when there is nothing else.
=C2=A0
As I enjoy cooking, I also frequently =
cook other general (i.e. non-saattwik) food items for family. When I do tha=
t, I may taste what I make.I also occasionally eat at restaurants with fami=
ly. In other words, I try to eat saattwik food as far as possible, but not =
100% strict at the moment. There was a period in the past when I was.

=C2=
=A0
*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=
=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *
=C2=A0
No natural food is universally good or bad. Oni=
ons (especially raw), for example, are awful for a vata person like me. But=
 they are cooling and awesome for a pitta person.
=C2=A0
Chocolates are not=
 that bad in moderation - the main problem with chocolates is that they are=
 heavily processed. Cacao beans are artificially processed to make cocoa bu=
tter, cocoa liquor etc, which is used in chocolates.Now-a-days, for lowerin=
g the price, chocolate companies in US are even using Polyglycerol polyrici=
noleate (PGPR), which, though safe in small quantities, is related to the p=
oison ricin. Now-a-days, processed food is all about low price, loooong she=
lf life and having a uniform consistency and texture, rather than actual go=
odness.

=C2=A0
I avoid most processed foods and make my food from basic, n=
atural, raw ingredients as far as possible. As for chocolate and hot chocol=
ate, I occasionally enjoy a tea made of milk, cardamom powder, raw sugar an=
d unprocessed organic cacao bean powder. This simpler version of hot chocol=
ate is probably closer to what ancient Mayans enjoyed (and called the "drin=
k of gods"), compared to the *heavily* processed "hot chocolate" sold by mo=
dern brands. Though cacao beans are drying to the body and not great for a =
vata person like me, they are better than coffee and tea. So I take it occa=
sionally for the flavinoids in them.
=C2=A0
Balance is the key. Eat what is=
 good for you 80% of the time. Eat other things now and then, but balance t=
hem with ingredients that compensate for their bad qualities. Then your bod=
y will get balanced nutrition. Some familiarity with ayurveda is very very =
useful (read "Prakriti: Your Ayurvedic Constitution" and "Yoga of Herbs"). =
The notions on nutrition and health in popular culture are utterly nonsensi=
cal.

=C2=A0

