>Even firewood logs will burn better and=
 brighter if they have air circulation. If a wood log touches fire pit bott=
om/walls only at its two edges and is suspended in air elsewhere, it will b=
urn better because of air supply. Otherwise, edges of the portion without a=
ir circulation may keep releasing smoke.
>
>=C2=A0
>As things burn, if you =
turn them around or mix them up so that everything burns well (tongs may be=
 used), it can help you burn everything well.
>=C2=A0When I offer poornahut=
i (a whole dry coconut) in my homam, I pre-arrange burnt wood coals in a st=
ructure that has nice air flow. When coconut is placed atop those coals, it=
 does not crush everything (in which case, some stuff under coconut or bott=
om of coconut may burn fully by the time fire goes off), but gets suspended=
 on the coals with most of the coconut getting air circulation. It burns ni=
cely from all sides, including the bottom. If this is not possible, you may=
 want to turn the poornahuti around in the middle (while there is still fir=
e) and perhaps change its position/place (and offer a little more ghee then=
). In my case, I go into one-hour japam after poornahuti and do not want to=
 stop meditation in the middle to take care of poornahuti. So I arrange thi=
ngs nicely beforehand. The way it is placed, it just burns completely and e=
verything offered before also burns completely, by the time fire goes off b=
y itself.
>=C2=A0
>It is a matter of understanding the dynamics of how fire=
